<font color="#FF0000">DOC SPATZ ? ON DRUGS</font><br>
<tt>Sat May 17  8:22:42 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
S2/S3 used to burn kilos of grass in an open area now and then, so I know it was around, and abundant. No one in my tribe used anything, at least to my knowledge. We couldn't function too well to protect the grunts. Artillery is not forgiving. They never perfected a round that corrected mistakes down range. You just didn't make mistakes!<br><br>
Stand downs, Vung Tau, Saigon, and the like were a different matter. I once stopped by a USO where you could by it through the fence, along with the kid's sister as a bonus. The pushers were children, teenagers. For a few p you could get anything, anywhere, anytime. Greenbacks really talked. Many guys really cut loose when the pressure was off. I don't blame them for that. The place drove some crazy. <br><br>
I do recall some talk now and then of a grunt or two in the bush, but most of it was in the larger basecamps and towns, as Doc Del has indicated.<br><br>
Lets face it. To stay alive you needed all your wits. If you are stoned, the trip wire you missed would be your last, or your buddy could get blown away, too. Have your buddy get blown away, and you are really left with a living hell.<br><br>
Booze was a REAL problem. The Army pipeline really kept it flowing. There were more alcoholics around than I could count, and it was legal, too! Lifers were especially prone to really hit the sauce, but they did that stateside too. Then again, most of the lifers hid out in the basecamps, anyway. Their mistakes, the wrong ball bearings or toilet seats, never amounted to squat. Pardon my bitterness, but some of them personally didn't amount to squat either.<br><br>
I'm wandering. Back to your questions.<br><br>
I personally did not use drugs in Nam. I have never used drugs in the 50 years of my life. I probably had only 4 or 5 cans of beer during my tour in Nam. It just didn't fit what I was there to do. I couldn't live with myself otherwise.<br><br>

